{
  "texts": [
    "During training or fine-tuning, malicious agents like Trojan low-rank adapters 44 can hijack models to execute foreign code.",
    "Models may also contain intentional backdoors immune to traditional safety-tuning procedures 45.",
    "Specific models may be corrupted through prompt-based learning 46, 47 and instruction tuning 48, or their weights may be directly edited to encode harmful biomedical facts without affecting other concepts [49] [50] [51].",
    "Proprietary LLMs are no exception to these risks, and creative prompt engineering can jailbreak built-in guardrails to leak confidential information and access files from other users' sessions [52] [53] [54] [55] [56].",
    "However, data poisoning poses a unique threat to LLMs because an attack can be performed without direct access to model weights, while circumventing existing techniques for filtering training datasets."
  ]
}